Setup the library¶

import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
%matplotlib inline

Function¶

In [2]:
def noise_img(img):
    # make array of zeros
    noise = np.zeros(img.shape)
    # random the value between 0 and 255
    cv2.randu(noise, 0, 256)
    # combine it
    noisy = img + 0.2*noise
    return noisy
In [3]:
def show_img(initial, final, imsg='Original', msg='Converted'):
    # setup figure 
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    # first column
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.title(imsg)
    plt.imshow(initial, cmap='gray')
    # second column
    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.title(msg)
    plt.imshow(final, cmap='gray')
    plt.show()
In [4]:
def linear(img, K, L):
    # convert to array of int
    img = np.asarray(img, dtype=np.int)
    img = img*K + L
    # make sure the range is in [0,255]
    img[img > 255] = 255
    img[img < 0] = 0
    return img

Noise¶

In [5]:
house = cv2.imread('images/house.jpg',0)
noisy_img = noise_img(house)
show_img(house, noisy_img, msg='Noised')

Linear¶

In [6]:
linear = linear(house, 2, -100)
cv2.imwrite('linear.jpg', linear)
show_img(house, linear, msg='Linear')

Box Filter¶

or Mean Filter

In [7]:
mountain = cv2.imread('images/mountain.jpg')
blur5 = cv2.blur(mountain, (5,5))
blur10 = cv2.blur(mountain, (10,10))
blur20 = cv2.blur(mountain, (20,20))
show_img(mountain, blur5, msg='Blur 5x5')
show_img(blur10, blur20, imsg='Blur 10x10', msg='Blur 20x20')

Median Filter¶

In [8]:
penguin = cv2.imread('images/penguin.png')
median3 = cv2.medianBlur(penguin, 3)
median5 = cv2.medianBlur(penguin, 5)
median7 = cv2.medianBlur(penguin, 7)
show_img(penguin, median3, msg='Median 3x3')
show_img(median5, median7, imsg='Median 5x5', msg='Median 7x7')
